00:00.000 --> 00:07.000
I am a teacher of the Moscow Business School and head the department of programs on leadership and personal effectiveness.

00:07.000 --> 00:16.000
I have 20 years of experience in business education, of which 10 years I headed the HR department in large insurance and financial companies.

00:16.000 --> 00:23.000
Within the framework of the program, I have a lot of experience in the field of business management,

00:23.000 --> 00:38.000
and I am glad to be here today to discuss two issues – the power and leadership in the organization.

00:38.000 --> 00:42.000
First, I will tell you one parable.

00:42.000 --> 00:47.000
A peasant saved a daoist who was drowning.

00:47.000 --> 00:51.000
The daoist decided to thank the peasant and brought him to his hut.

00:51.000 --> 01:00.000
He took a pumpkin from the shed, from which he took out three things – a needle, a hammer and a scythe.

01:00.000 --> 01:03.000
He put these things at the feet of the peasant and said,

01:03.000 --> 01:10.000
These things may not seem to be of great importance, but each of them has a magical power.

01:10.000 --> 01:13.000
The needle gives you life and eternal health.

01:13.000 --> 01:18.000
The hammer cuts out gold and silver coins when struck.

01:18.000 --> 01:24.000
And the scythe gives you power to defeat any army and all enemies.

01:24.000 --> 01:30.000
You saved my life, so you can choose whatever you want.

01:30.000 --> 01:35.000
The peasant thought for a while. He took the needle and put it behind his belt.

01:35.000 --> 01:39.000
You made a quick decision, said the daoist.

01:39.000 --> 01:44.000
Don't you care about wealth and power?

01:44.000 --> 01:48.000
I chose life, said the peasant.

01:48.000 --> 01:54.000
If I have it, I will have power and money if I want it.

01:54.000 --> 02:01.000
Did the old man act wisely? I often ask this question to students at lectures at the university.

02:01.000 --> 02:04.000
They laugh. No, of course.

02:04.000 --> 02:06.000
You had to choose a hammer.

02:06.000 --> 02:12.000
When you have money, you can buy whatever you want, even health.

02:12.000 --> 02:15.000
But most students answer,

02:15.000 --> 02:18.000
You should have chosen a scythe.

02:18.000 --> 02:23.000
If you have power, they will do everything you order.

02:23.000 --> 02:27.000
Yes, indeed, in the everyday lives of people,

02:27.000 --> 02:33.000
the word power is perceived as a demonic force that should be worshiped,

02:33.000 --> 02:38.000
and as a cult force that must be respected.

02:38.000 --> 02:41.000
If you open the Dalia dictionary,

02:41.000 --> 02:46.000
the word power is defined in three definitions.

02:46.000 --> 02:51.000
Right, strength, and the will to do something.

02:51.000 --> 02:54.000
This is freedom of action.

02:54.000 --> 03:00.000
Today we will consider the concept of power within the framework of organizational behavior.

03:00.000 --> 03:06.000
Power is the potential ability to influence the behavior of other people,

03:06.000 --> 03:10.000
change the course of events, overcome resistance,

03:10.000 --> 03:17.000
make people do what they would not do under other circumstances.

03:17.000 --> 03:25.000
In other words, power is the potential ability to mobilize resources to achieve something

03:25.000 --> 03:30.000
without looking back at any organizational counteraction.

03:30.000 --> 03:38.000
How can we use political power in an organization to achieve the most effective results in business?

03:38.000 --> 03:46.000
What hidden motives of human behavior can be used in the process of power realization?

03:46.000 --> 03:51.000
There are several types of power sources

03:51.000 --> 03:59.000
that a manager or a manager can use in the process of managing staff.

03:59.000 --> 04:04.000
So, power based on incentives.

04:04.000 --> 04:11.000
Does a person have the opportunities and resources that can be used for incentives?

04:11.000 --> 04:21.000
It is important to understand that the key figure in the process of realizing this type of power is the employee.

04:21.000 --> 04:26.000
Because if he does not accept and appreciate the reward,

04:26.000 --> 04:30.000
then there is no power based on reward.

04:30.000 --> 04:32.000
I will give you a simple example.

04:32.000 --> 04:37.000
Remember, children in school, who do not always succeed in their peers,

04:37.000 --> 04:43.000
very often bring sweets and treat them to the names of other children

04:43.000 --> 04:49.000
in order to use the power over others.

04:49.000 --> 04:53.000
Power is based on punishment.

04:53.000 --> 04:58.000
It is based on the expectation of punishment in the event of disobedience.

04:59.000 --> 05:05.000
As an example, remember the situation in the USSR in the 30s and 40s,

05:05.000 --> 05:12.000
when it was the power based on punishment that kept the masses of people in submission.

05:12.000 --> 05:20.000
This type of power is very beneficial to apply in critical and crisis situations in a company.

05:20.000 --> 05:24.000
Power based on legitimacy.

05:24.000 --> 05:29.000
It is based on the regulation of the behavior of subordinates to the authorities

05:29.000 --> 05:34.000
and the insistent requirement to comply with these regulations.

05:34.000 --> 05:41.000
As an example of legitimate power, we can use the Constitution of the state.

05:41.000 --> 05:46.000
The law is created, adopted by the people,

05:46.000 --> 05:52.000
and the representative of the authorities has the right to demand compliance with these laws.

05:53.000 --> 05:55.000
Referential power.

05:55.000 --> 05:58.000
Power based on likeness.

05:58.000 --> 06:04.000
When a person associates himself with a person in power.

06:04.000 --> 06:15.000
There is a very important condition that the leader must be competent and successful in the eyes of his subordinates.

06:15.000 --> 06:20.000
Only then will the referential power work.

06:20.000 --> 06:23.000
Expert power.

06:23.000 --> 06:30.000
Expert power is based on the fact that its bearer must have deep professional knowledge.

06:30.000 --> 06:38.000
It is well known that the more unique knowledge an employee has, the more power he has.

06:38.000 --> 06:43.000
That is why today there are very often situations in companies

06:43.000 --> 06:50.000
when employees are reluctant to share their accumulated professional and even life experience.

06:50.000 --> 06:58.000
In this regard, there is a system of knowledge management adopted in the company,

06:58.000 --> 07:08.000
when employees are motivated to share their professional experience with their colleagues.

07:09.000 --> 07:15.000
There are a number of factors that affect the process of power implementation.

07:15.000 --> 07:23.000
These factors either strengthen the power in the organization or weaken it.

07:23.000 --> 07:26.000
Let's look at these factors.

07:26.000 --> 07:29.000
So, uncertainty.

07:29.000 --> 07:33.000
This is related to the self-esteem of a person or a group of people.

07:34.000 --> 07:41.000
It is known that if a person is not confident in himself and his actions, it is easier for him to influence.

07:41.000 --> 07:43.000
The gender.

07:43.000 --> 07:50.000
Scientists have proven that women are easier to be subject to power than men.

07:50.000 --> 08:00.000
However, experiments and evidence of recent times put women on equal terms with men.

08:00.000 --> 08:05.000
This affects not only business, but social life in general.

08:05.000 --> 08:08.000
Intellect.

08:08.000 --> 08:19.000
It is known that people with more advanced intelligence listen to other people more attentively, more willingly, and more empathetically.

08:19.000 --> 08:21.000
Age.

08:21.000 --> 08:28.000
Scientists have proven that children under 9 years of age are most affected.

08:28.000 --> 08:37.000
After that, the impact remains approximately at the same level as those formed in a person before the age of 9.

08:37.000 --> 08:39.000
Culture.

08:39.000 --> 08:41.000
Cultural values.

08:41.000 --> 08:53.000
Scientists have proven that Asian cultures are most affected, because their values are based on loyalty and consent.

08:53.000 --> 09:03.000
European cultures are less affected, because their values are based on individual self-expression.

09:03.000 --> 09:11.000
And the personal quality of a person is another factor that affects the process of power implementation.

09:11.000 --> 09:30.000
It is well known that people in difficult situations with low self-esteem, who expect support from a stronger person, are more affected by power than people with a calm and stable rhythm of life.

09:30.000 --> 09:37.000
The general situational model of power was described quite well by French Raiven and Kelman.

09:37.000 --> 09:44.000
They focused their model on four main factors, which you see now on the slide.

09:44.000 --> 09:50.000
One of them is the required source of power, which we have just discussed.

09:50.000 --> 09:54.000
The second is the process of implementation.

09:55.000 --> 10:02.000
This is how the object of power should behave so that the process of power takes place.

10:02.000 --> 10:08.000
The third factor is the subjectivity of the object of power to influence.

10:08.000 --> 10:15.000
In other words, what motivates, what moves a person at the time of power implementation.

10:16.000 --> 10:28.000
And the necessary conditions for the implementation of power as a result of which the object and subject of power want to receive from interaction.

10:28.000 --> 10:34.000
Thus, the situational model of power looks like this.

10:35.000 --> 10:46.000
It can help you in your further work, when you are engaged in organizational diagnostics and study organizational behavior and corporate culture of your company.

10:46.000 --> 10:52.000
Let's look at one of the examples. It is highlighted in blue on my slide.

10:52.000 --> 10:57.000
So, the required source of power, for example, is compulsion.

10:57.000 --> 11:08.000
For the implementation of this source of power, it is necessary to organize or motivate an employee to obey.

11:08.000 --> 11:16.000
The motivating factor of the object of power is the desire to avoid punishment from the subject of power.

11:16.000 --> 11:26.000
And, accordingly, the necessary conditions for the implementation of this process of power are constant supervision of the object.

11:26.000 --> 11:41.000
Thus, according to this situational model, you can study and review all the sources of power, the process of its implementation, subjectivity of the object to influence and the necessary conditions.

11:41.000 --> 11:48.000
So, power and organizational policy intertwine very closely.

11:48.000 --> 12:06.000
Organizational policy is a complex of intended methods of influence, undertaken by a person or a group of people in order to strengthen or protect their own interests when possible alternatives arise.

12:07.000 --> 12:17.000
It is generally known today that political games, so-called political games, exist in all formal organizations.

12:18.000 --> 12:26.000
It is generally proven that the fewer political games, the more effective the organization works.

12:26.000 --> 12:36.000
And, in turn, the more active political games are played, the less effective the organization moves towards achieving its goal.

12:36.000 --> 12:43.000
Let's now look at the spheres that affect the political nature.

12:44.000 --> 12:49.000
Resources. These are financial resources.

12:49.000 --> 13:01.000
It is generally known that to implement political games in an organization, more resources are always needed than they are declared in organizational documents.

13:01.000 --> 13:03.000
Goals.

13:03.000 --> 13:20.000
The more vague the goals of the organization are, the less clearly they are spelled out, the organization creates a kind of chaos and misunderstanding, which allows the emergence of political games.

13:20.000 --> 13:25.000
Decisions. Another sphere that affects the political nature.

13:25.000 --> 13:40.000
It is generally known that the more vague the decisions in an organization are, the longer they are adopted, the more they strengthen the political games within the organization.

13:40.000 --> 13:43.000
No solutions, as they say, no problems.

13:43.000 --> 13:59.000
Technologies. It is generally known that the more complex the technologies within the company are, the more complex the hierarchy built into the organization, the more it strengthens the political nature of organizational behavior.

13:59.000 --> 14:14.000
And changes. We know that changes are an inevitable process in any organization. It allows the organization to develop due to the existing temporary crises in it.

14:14.000 --> 14:36.000
Therefore, it is impossible to avoid changes in organizational behavior. And you don't have to strive to do it. It is very important how much top management and the company's management can manage changes in the organization in order to minimize the political nature of organizational behavior.

14:36.000 --> 14:55.000
I will give you a simple example. When Jack Welch was appointed the CEO of General Electric, the first thing he did was to review all five spheres that strengthen the political nature of the company and influence each of them.

14:55.000 --> 15:15.000
He set clear goals, embodied the organizational structure, minimized all technological processes in the company, prepared people for the skill of managing changes and clearly specified all the incoming and outgoing resources of the company.

15:15.000 --> 15:37.000
Now you can open a workbook, this is a case, in which the real business situation is described and you need to answer the questions asked, which will allow you to consolidate your knowledge in the field of leadership theories and in the field of power in the organization.

15:37.000 --> 15:44.000
What is power?

16:07.000 --> 16:31.000
On the contrary, we very often meet leaders in the organization who are not leaders. In this block, we will consider all the existing theories of leadership study, as well as the modern problems of leadership and the latest theories of discovery in this field.

16:31.000 --> 16:45.000
So, what is leadership? How to assess leadership qualities? What kind of person is a leader in our idea today? And what distinguishes him from a non-leader?

16:45.000 --> 17:06.000
Let's first get acquainted with the definition of leadership. Leadership is an attempt by the leader, using different sources of power and his own set of skills, to influence a group of people and direct their efforts to achieve the goal.

17:07.000 --> 17:31.000
Let's look at one example. Here is a description of three candidates. These are the leaders of their era, who have great power. I suggest you, according to your inner values and criteria, to determine a person who, in your opinion, is the ideal example of a leader.

17:31.000 --> 17:47.000
So, candidate A is associated with dishonest politicians and consults with astrologers. He has two girlfriends, he smokes a lot and drinks up to 8 glasses of martini every day. Not a very pleasant image.

17:47.000 --> 18:01.000
Candidate B is a student who has been expelled from college twice, he used to drink opium, now he sleeps until noon and drinks a liter of whiskey every day. Probably, this is possible.

18:01.000 --> 18:12.000
And candidate B is a hero of war, a vegetarian, does not smoke, in special cases only drinks beer, has no intercourse.

18:12.000 --> 18:27.000
I am often told by my course listeners that the ideal leader is candidate B. I dare to assume that you, too, have involuntarily drawn to the choice of this particular person.

18:27.000 --> 18:43.000
Let's see now, let's open the secrets, who is who. So, candidate A is Franklin Roosevelt, candidate B is Winston Churchill and candidate B is Adolf Hitler.

18:43.000 --> 19:12.000
Please note that all three candidates are unrivaled leaders of their era and not only of their country, but of the whole world. However, each of them, you may have noticed, has not only unique leadership qualities, but if you compare them, these qualities are in stark contradiction with each other.

19:13.000 --> 19:28.000
This is where the history of leadership study began, which eventually came and was divided into three approaches. Personal, behavioral and situational.

19:28.000 --> 19:47.000
Now we will consider what is the personal approach in the theory of leadership study, who was its founder, what is the essence of the personal approach, what are the advantages and disadvantages of this theory.

19:47.000 --> 20:09.000
So, the earliest stage of the study of leadership qualities is based on the analysis of qualities that a leader needs to manage. In other words, scientists tried to explain what qualities distinguish a leader from a non-leader.

20:09.000 --> 20:31.000
They dared to assume that leaders have a certain set of qualities that are given to a person by nature and never change over time. Therefore, if you were born a leader, then you will be a leader. And if you were not born a leader with certain qualities, then you will never become a leader.

20:31.000 --> 20:48.000
This is how Teodor Tiet wrote the book The Art of a Leader for the first time. With the publication of this book in 1935, the theory of the personal approach and the theory of leadership qualities emerged.

20:48.000 --> 21:07.000
Please note how Tiet described the basic qualities of a leader. For this purpose, he conducted a study of a very large number of great people of his time, in which he tried to find qualities that unite them.

21:07.000 --> 21:23.000
Here is what Tiet's picture looks like. Physical and emotional endurance, understanding of the purpose of an organization and the direction of its activities, enthusiasm, friendliness, the disposition of others, and orderliness.

21:23.000 --> 21:46.000
A few years later, Robert Stockdill tried to conduct a similar experiment. He also collected a certain number of great people of his time and tried to describe their qualities and determine the key competencies or qualities that unite all the leaders they study.

21:46.000 --> 22:01.000
Here is what Stockdill's picture looks like. The main qualities of a leader are intelligence and intellectual abilities, dominance or dominance over others, self-confidence, activity, energy and knowledge of affairs.

22:01.000 --> 22:18.000
However, the most interesting achievement in the field of studying the qualities of a leader belongs to Oran Bennis. He conducted the following experiment.

22:18.000 --> 22:36.000
Robert Stockdill compared the qualities of great people of his time and found out the qualities of a leader that distinguish these people from non-leaders. Oran Bennis made a parallel between a leader and a manager.

22:36.000 --> 23:00.000
If you look at the table on the slide, you can see that all the qualities that are signed under the manager distinguish a leader from a non-leader. That is, the qualities that, according to Bennis, do not belong to the leader, but to the manager.

23:00.000 --> 23:16.000
Bennis said that a leader is a guiding image, passion and integrity. That is, he is an inspirer of his ideas, which calls people to action, but does not organize the process.

23:16.000 --> 23:36.000
Thus, the theories of the qualities of a leader have calculated more than 80 competences by the end of the Second World War. Is it possible to combine 80 qualities of a leader in one person? Of course not.

23:36.000 --> 23:52.000
Moreover, these 80 qualities of a leader, which, according to the research, scientists found, are impossible to combine in one person, because they often contradict each other.

23:52.000 --> 24:08.000
If we look at the three leading images that scientists and researchers of that time have, you will see that they are completely different in image, temperament and type of people.

24:08.000 --> 24:28.000
Thus, by the end of the Second World War, it became obvious that it was impossible to invent the qualities of a leader. There is no such person with such qualities, who could be taken as the ideal of a leader and, accordingly, other successors could be selected for him.

24:28.000 --> 24:49.000
This is a minus of the theory of the personal approach. Plus, the theory of the personal approach became a push for subsequent researches of scientists, who began to study not the leader's qualities, but the models of behavior of leaders.

24:49.000 --> 25:07.000
In other words, the essence of the behavioral approach is not the qualities that determine a person as a leader or not, but certain models of behavior that a certain person transmits.

25:07.000 --> 25:31.000
Let's define the concept of a leader's style. Remember, in Greek, the word style meant a pen. Subsequently, we began to associate the word pen with the word handwriting, that is, the manifestation of individuality. Thus, style is a manifestation of individuality.

25:31.000 --> 25:48.000
In turn, the leader's style is a model of the behavior of a leader, used to influence a group of people and to direct efforts to achieve a common goal. It is important to note that this is a model of the behavior of a leader.

25:48.000 --> 26:05.000
The first person to propose the theory of the behavior model of a leader was a psychologist Kurt Levin. He conducted a very unusual experiment with a group of boys who made theatrical masks.

26:05.000 --> 26:28.000
The age of the boys was 10-12 years. Kurt Levin appointed the leader of this group and asked him to broadcast different styles of management over a certain period of time. The first of them is authoritarian, when the power is concentrated in the hands of the leader.

26:28.000 --> 26:48.000
The effectiveness of the work was very high. The number of masks produced by the boys broke all records over a certain period of time. After that, the leader was offered to change the leader's style and become a more democratic leader.

26:48.000 --> 27:05.000
What happened? The number of masks produced sharply decreased. There were much fewer of them, but they were different from the previous masks, more creative and more unusual in execution.

27:05.000 --> 27:24.000
Thus, Kurt Levin came to the conclusion that the most effective style or model of behavior of the leader is authoritarian, because the experience of the boys indicated the high workability and effectiveness of the group of people.

27:24.000 --> 27:44.000
However, he did not take into account the fact that the masks produced by the boys under the leadership of the authoritarian leader were not different in terms of creative approach, variety, or creativity. Yes, there were really more of them.

27:44.000 --> 27:58.000
This was the disadvantage of Kurt Levin's research. Now we will briefly focus on the results of the research conducted at the Michigan University and the University of Ohio.

27:58.000 --> 28:23.000
The main concept of these studies is that the style of leadership proposed by the researchers is either oriented towards workers, high orientation towards interpersonal relations in the group, or towards the task, towards production, high concentration on the production and technical aspects of the work.

28:23.000 --> 28:36.000
Subsequently, the research of the Michigan University and the University of Ohio became the basis for the development of more advanced methods of behavioral theory of leadership.

28:36.000 --> 28:57.000
One of them we will now consider in more detail. This is the management grid of Robert Blake and Jane Moulton. Robert Blake and Jane Moulton arranged all the styles of behavior, and there are only 81 of them, according to their concept, on two axes.

28:57.000 --> 29:14.000
Please pay attention to the following. The vertical axis is the degree of accounting for the interests of people, and the horizontal axis is the degree of accounting for the interests of production. On a 9-point scale, there is an axis on the vertical and an axis on the horizontal.

29:14.000 --> 29:27.000
Thus, according to the management grid of Blake and Moulton, there are 81 styles of behavior of the leader. Let's take a brief look at each of them.

29:27.000 --> 29:44.000
So, the 1-9 square is the high degree of orientation towards interpersonal relations in the group and the very low orientation of the leadership towards the task. The so-called management in the spirit of a suburban club.

29:44.000 --> 30:06.000
The 1-1 square is called the poor management, when the orientation towards the interests of people in the company is very low, and at the same time the low orientation towards the tasks of production. This is considered the most unacceptable style, as you understand, and this is obvious.

30:06.000 --> 30:22.000
The 9-1 square is the high degree of orientation towards the tasks and the extremely low degree of orientation towards the interests of people. The so-called authority of subordination. The authoritarian style of management.

30:22.000 --> 30:47.000
The 9-9 square is the so-called group management, where the orientation towards the interests of the employee, the interpersonal relations within the group and, to the same extent, the high orientation towards the interests of production and tasks. According to the concept of Moulton and Blake, this is the ideal style of management.

30:47.000 --> 31:04.000
There is also an intermediate style of management, the 5-5 square, the so-called organizational management, when the need for production results and the maintenance of people's moral attitude at a decent level is balanced.

31:04.000 --> 31:24.000
In business, the manager very often makes a fluctuation between the 1-9 style and the 9-9 style. In reality, you will rarely find a situation today when the manager is focused on both the management style and the other style.

31:24.000 --> 31:50.000
What is the disadvantage of the Moulton and Blake management grid? They unambiguously recognize the 9-9 square as the ideal style of management. However, it is not always proven whether the 9-9 style or the so-called group management will be effective in all situations.

31:50.000 --> 32:06.000
Moreover, we have previously said that in crisis and critical situations in the organization, the 9-9 style is not always acceptable and not always effective in the process of changing the current company.

32:06.000 --> 32:25.000
I think it will be interesting for you to recall, if you already know about it, or to remind and tell, if you do not know about it, about the motivational theory of Douglas MacGregor, who called it the theory of X and Y.

32:36.000 --> 33:05.000
However, later the theory of Y emerged from Douglas MacGregor, who said that a person is a being capable of self-realization.

33:06.000 --> 33:23.000
And people consider work a natural state, there is no need to push, force and direct a person to creativity. This is what the theory of motivation X and Y, which belongs to MacGregor, looks like in general.

33:23.000 --> 33:42.000
However, all behavioral approaches that I have suggested are excluded by one important factor. Behavioral models are clear. Authoritarian, task-oriented, democratic, interpersonal.

33:42.000 --> 34:07.000
At the same time, none of the researchers has given the most important arguments in which situations, with which employees, it is necessary to apply this or that style of management. In other words, the researchers did not take into account situational factors that determine the success or failure of the group.

34:07.000 --> 34:24.000
Thus, in the theories of behavioral approach, I summarize the above, factors describing the needs and personal qualities of employees, the nature of the task, the requirements and the impact of the environment were not taken into account.

34:24.000 --> 34:52.000
Take, for example, Martin Luther King Jr. was unlikely to have a chance to become a prominent leader in civil rights, for example, in 1900. However, he became such in 1950-1960. Everything depends on the situation and the time in which the leader is.

34:53.000 --> 35:17.000
Thus, the theories of behavioral approach became a powerful impetus for the development of the next direction in the study of leadership, situational leadership, when not only behavioral models, the qualities and competencies of the leader, but also the situation in which the leader was and is in one or another time were taken into account.

35:18.000 --> 35:27.000
Let's first decide what situational leadership is. This is, I remind you, the third approach in the theory of leadership study.

35:27.000 --> 35:46.000
Situational leadership involves the interaction and influence of various factors on the behavior of the leader. These situational factors include the needs and personal qualities of employees, the nature of the task, the requirements and the impact of the environment.

35:46.000 --> 36:01.000
As you already understand, situational leadership does not create, but continues the experience of previous studies, when the interests of the group and the interests of the situation are taken into account.

36:01.000 --> 36:15.000
One of the most interesting solutions, one of the most interesting theories in the field of situational leadership, today in business we call the model of situational leadership the Hersey and Blanchard.

36:15.000 --> 36:36.000
What is the focus of this theory and what do its researchers focus on? If you pay attention to the square consisting of four planes, the behavior of the leader is oriented to the attitude in the team and to the task.

36:36.000 --> 36:51.000
Remember, this is very similar to the management grid of Moulton and Blake from the theory of behavioral approach. However, what is the difference between the situational leadership of Hersey and Blanchard and the behavioral grid of Moulton and Blake?

36:51.000 --> 37:10.000
You probably remember that there were not taken into account the interests, needs, level of readiness, task structure of the employees. It was in this grid that Hersey and Blanchard took into account the behavior of the employee at different stages of his development.

37:10.000 --> 37:39.000
In this scheme, this is denoted by the letters S1, S2, S3 and S4. The model of situational leadership of Hersey and Blanchard implies four styles of behavior of the leader, starting from the strict and directive, moving to the mentor, then the supportive, and at the end, when the employee is completely ready and completely built up,

